%I A393129 #22 Apr 07 2026 23:45:54
%S A393129 1,2,13,121,192,237,288,1665,1825,3117
%N A393129 Numbers k such that there is a reversible prime of the form 10^k - 2*10^m - 1.
%C A393129 "Reversible prime" means a palindromic (here: wing) prime (A077798, subset of A002385) or an emirp (cf. A006567). The near-repdigit primes considered here have k digits 9 except for one digit 7, see Examples.
%C A393129 The definition implies that 0 <= m < k, and we can assume WLOG m < k/2; then 10^k - 2*10^m - 1 is the larger and 10^k - 2*10^(k-m-1) - 1 is the smaller of the two emirps, unless 2m = k-1, in which case its a palindromic wing prime (PWP).
%e A393129 For k = 1, m = 0, we have 10^1 - 1 - 2*10^0 = 7, a palindromic prime.
%e A393129 For k = 2, m = 0, we have 10^2 - 1 - 2*10^0 = 97, an emirp (with reverse prime 79).
%e A393129 For k = 13, m = 2, we have 10^k - 1 - 2*10^m = 9999999999799, again an emirp, with reverse prime 9979999999999.
%o A393129 (PARI) is_A393129(k, r=10^k-1)=for(m=0, k\/2-1, ispseudoprime(r-10^(k-m-1)*2)&& ispseudoprime(r-10^m*2)&& return(m-!m)) /* return the m-value if it exists (but -1 if m=0), else 0 */
%o A393129 for(k=1, oo, is_A393129(k) && print1(k", "))
%Y A393129 Cf. A393126, A393130, A393131 (similar with distinct digit 8, 5 and 4, respectively).
%Y A393129 Cf. A006567 (emirps), A004086 (n with digits reversed), A173594 (near-repdigit emirps).
%Y A393129 Cf. A002385 (palindromic primes), A077798 (palindromic wing primes).
%K A393129 nonn,hard,more,base
%O A393129 1,2
%A A393129 _M. F. Hasler_, Mar 24 2026
%E A393129 a(8)-a(10) from _Michael S. Branicky_, Mar 25 2026
